  abstract     = {Data analysis often entails a multitude of
    heterogeneous steps, from the application of various command line
    tools to the usage of scripting languages like R or Python for the
    generation of plots and tables. It is widely recognized that data
    analyses should ideally be conducted in a reproducible
    way.\&nbsp;Reproducibility enables technical validation and
    regeneration of results on the original or even new data. However,
    reproducibility alone is by no means sufficient to deliver an
    analysis that is of lasting impact (i.e., sustainable) for the
    field, or even just one research group. We postulate that it is
    equally important to ensure adaptability and transparency. The
    former describes the ability to modify the analysis to answer
    extended or slightly different research questions. The latter
    describes the ability to understand the analysis in order to judge
